{        Which Suit to Lead (in order of preference)        }
^-|CS||FP|2|CP|8|AT|^C@2^Y@3
1. Partner's suit|CP||AT| – one of my cardinal rules is always lead your partner's suit. You never lose the post mortem by leading partner's suit. There are occasional exceptions, but they are very rare. Therefore, if you always lead your partner's suit, you will come out way ahead. Plus, just as importantly, you will build partnership trust. If I do not lead partner's suit, partner can assume I have a void. |
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

2. |CP|8|AT|Unbid suit. |CP||
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT|

3. |CP|8|AT|Longest suit|CP||AT| (against NT contracts). |
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


AT|

4. |CP|8|AT|Suits with an honor sequence|CP||AT| (see below for details on honor sequence leads). |
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT|

5. |CP|8|AT|Trump|CP||AT| (see below). |
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|

6. |CP|8|AT|Singleton|CP||AT| – you should either have a trump trick or good reason to believe partner may have the Ace or a trump trick.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


