^-|CP||FP||cp|8|AT|^C@2^Y@3
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As many of you know, I work closely with Marty Bergen who is one of the best bridge players in the US. He told me, on hands where the opening lead matters, and it is not obvious, he is happy if he gets half of them right. If Marty Bergen only gets half right, then we can feel good if we get half right.|
PG| ***** 167 ***** |


AT|

There are basically 2 considerations when considering your opening lead. The first and more important is which suit. Once you pick the suit, then you have to decide which card in that suit.|
PG| ***** 168 ***** |


AT|

Let me give you some general guidelines about which suits to lead. There are few absolute rules in bridge. But, this first principle is one of two cardinal principles that I always obey
and that is, ALWAYS LEAD YOUR PARTNER'S SUIT.|
PG| ***** 169 ***** |


AT|

Most of the time it will be right, or at least not wrong
and, more importantly, it builds partnership trust. My partners know, if I don't lead their suit, I probably have a void
and, as I tell my partners, if you lead my suit, you can never lose the post mortem :). It might not be right on the hand, but is right for the partnership. I have followed this rule for many years, and I assure you I have come out ahead in the long run. So, that is my first and most important rule.|
PG| ***** 170 ***** |


AT|

The second order of preference in choosing a suit is to choose an unbid suit. Some people think that if someone opens one of a minor, it's okay to lead the minor, because sometimes opener is short. That is not true. If someone opens one of a minor, 85% or more of the time they have four plus cards in the suit. And even if they only have three cards, they usually have honors. So, avoid leading any suits that the opponents have bid. This is not an absolute rule, but it is a very good guideline. |
PG| ***** 171 ***** |


nT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%
HT|d|FP|1|cs|1|CP|4|at|^-
{        Transcript from the Lesson       }
^-|CP||FP||cp|8|AT|^C@2^Y@3
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Against NT contracts, my preference is to lead my longest unbid suit. I prefer length over strength. The longer my suit, the more likely in NT I am going to set up my low cards. If I own two unbid suits of the same length, then I pick the stronger one. So, the old "4th from longest and strongest" rule does work well. Some people say you should prefer to lead an unbid major and there is some merit to that, in that modern bidding tends to focus on bidding major over minors. So, failure to bid a major means that it is less likely that the opponents have that major. However, I still prefer to lead my longest and strongest suit, even if it is a minor.|
PG| ***** 172 ***** |


AT|

If it is close to a tie in terms of which suit to lead, then I will lead the major. But, that is only when it is close to a tie. Otherwise I pick my longest and strongest suit. Obviously, I was talking about if partner has not bid. Remember your first obligation is to lead partner's suit if partner has bid a suit.|
PG| ***** 173 ***** |


AT|

The next thing to consider are honor sequences, particularly against suit contracts. If you have 2 or more touching honors in an unbid suit, that is often a good lead. I will go over later which card to lead, but honor sequences tend to be strong leads in unbid suits.|
PG| ***** 174 ***** |


AT|

Another good lead is trumps. I will discuss specifically when trumps are a good lead in a few minutes. However "when in doubt, lead trumps" is not a good rule in general. I will clarify it in a few minutes.|
PG| ***** 175 ***** |


