^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Finally, another good lead is a singleton.

To summarize, in order of preference:
1) LEAD PARTNER"S SUIT
2) lead an unbid suit
3) lead longest and strongest unbid suit in NT
4) lead suits with an honor sequence
5) lead trumps on some hands
6) lead a singleton|
PG| ***** 176 ***** |


AT|

Let me give some examples. Assume you have the following distribution (the actual cards do not matter for this example)
@S ?? @H ??? @D ???? @C ????. Meaning, you have two spades, three hearts, four diamonds, and four clubs. Say the auction goes 1C-1S-double-P-2C-P-2H-P-P-P. In this auction, your partner overcalled 1@S. In this case it is obviously clear to lead a spade.|
PG| ***** 177 ***** |


AT|

Let's take a different auction. Again, remember you have two spades, three hearts, four diamonds, and four clubs. The auction is 1C-p-1D-p-1N-p-3N-all pass. In this case, lead a heart, the longest unbid suit. Even if you have honors in clubs or diamonds, avoid leading them. Perhaps if you had KQJ10 in a minor you might lead it. But, in general avoid leading suits that the opponents have bid.|
PG| ***** 178 ***** |


AT|

Here is 1C-P-1D-P-1H-P-2N-P-P-P auction. Here you should lead a spade. Partner rates to have five plus spades since neither opponent bid spades. There are exceptions to not leading a spade, but for now, just stick to unbid suits.|
PG| ***** 179 ***** |


