HT|d|FP|1|cs|1|CP|4|at|^-
{        Transcript from the Lesson       }
^-|CP||FP||cp|8|AT|^C@2^Y@3
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I am trying to give you simple but effective guidelines. And I have found leading unbid suits, in the long run, tends to work out well on more hands than not. You may come back to me and tell me on a specific hand, leading an unbid suit did not work out and I will not be surprised. However, I will be surprised if you tell me it rarely works out.|
PG| ***** 180 ***** |


AT|

I would like to clarify something here. If the opponents make an artificial bid, such as a transfer, or an artificial 2@C strong opener, they are not really showing the suit they bid. For example, if it goes 1N-P-2D (xfr)-P-2H. A diamond is a perfectly good lead because the 2D bidder did not show diamonds. So, when I said don't lead suits the opponents bid, I meant don't lead suits in which they have shown strength and length. If they make some conventional bid, in which the suit bid does not show strength or length in that suit, then leading that suit is fine.|
PG| ***** 181 ***** |


AT|

The final auction is 1C-P-1D-P-1H-P-3H-All pass. This is a prime candidate for a trump lead. You have length in the opponents suits and it sounds like each may be short in the other's suit. Therefore, here a trump lead (heart) would be called for. We will discuss this further shortly.|
PG| ***** 182 ***** |


AT|

Now, let's discuss which suits to avoid. First, as I said, avoid leading suits which the opponents have bid naturally. Second, leading away from an unprotected honor is often a bad lead. An "unprotected honor" is an honor that is not part of a sequence. So, a suit just as Kxxx and Qxxx contain unprotected honors. Leading those suits often gives away a trick, particularly in suit contracts. In NT contracts, you should not worry as much about leading away from unprotected honors in long suits, because you are trying to set up low cards. But, in suit contracts, you cannot set up low cards in your suits, because your opponent will probably be able to trump low cards. So, leading away from an unprotected honor in a suit contract should be avoided if possible (unless of course partner bid the suit).|
PG| ***** 183 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%
HT|d|FP|1|cs|1|CP|4|at|^-
{        Transcript from the Lesson       }
^-|CP||FP||cp|8|AT|^C@2^Y@3
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Here is another important rule that many less experienced players find hard to follow. This in regard to suits with unprotected Aces. Remember, an unprotected Ace is  when you don't have a sequence (e.g. the AK). Thus, in a suit where you don't have the A and K together, in a suit contract, don't lead that suit. First of all, you should never lead away from an Ace in a suit contract. If you lead a low card in a suit contract, partner should assume you cannot have the Ace. If you absolutely feel you have to lead the suit, then lead the Ace.|
PG| ***** 184 ***** |


AT|

Leading an Ace to "see what is going on" is a very bad idea. If you never lead an unprotected Ace for the rest of your bridge career, you will come out way ahead. Aces are made to capture other honors. Again, if partner bid the suit, it is ok to lead the Ace. And in NT, it is often good to lead away from an Ace. However, in suit contracts, avoid leading suits with unprotected Aces if partner has not bid the suit.|
PG| ***** 185 ***** |


AT|

Finally, and many people find this surprising, a doubleton is usually not a good lead. You rarely have the opportunity to set up a ruff for yourself. A singleton is a very strong lead
but a doubleton is a very weak lead.|
PG| ***** 186 ***** |


AT|

To summarize suits to avoid:
a) suits that opponents have bid naturally
b) away from unprotected honors in suit contracts (assuming partner has not bid the suit)
c) unprotected Aces or away from Aces in suit contracts (again assuming partner has not bid the suit)
d) leading doubletons|
PG| ***** 187 ***** |


NT||
HT|d|FP|1|cs|1|CP|4|at|^-
{        Transcript from the Lesson       }
^-|CP||FP||cp|8|AT|^C@2^Y@3
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is time to talk about when to lead trumps. You generally should lead trumps when you believe dummy or declarer is short in one of their partner's suit, and will be using trumps to trump losers in that suit. A common example is when declarer bids 2 suits, and responder supports one of those suits. It often means responder is short in the other of declarer's suit.|
PG| ***** 188 ***** |


AT|

Let me give an example. Suppose the auction is as follows: 1H-P-1S-P-2C-P-3C-P-P-P. On this contract, declarer has bid hearts and clubs, and partner has raised clubs, not hearts dummy is probably short in hearts, and since declarer has at least 5 hearts (remember declarer opened 1H), she will be trumping hearts in dummy. SO, a club lead is called for. This is a very common sort of auction when declarer shows 2 suits, and dummy takes a clear preference, a trump lead is usually a good lead. One more time; a good time to lead trumps is when declarer is 2 suited and responder has shown a preference.|
PG| ***** 189 ***** |


AT|

I got a question about what about if you have an honor in the trump suit.For example, the worst holding I can have when leading a trump is Qxx. That gets complicated. It is quite possible leading a trump will give up a trick. But, not leading a trump might also give up a trick. I would say in general, it is okay to lead a trump from Kxx or Axx, but not from Qxx or Jxx.|
PG| ***** 190 ***** |


AT|

Let's finish with what card to lead. The strongest lead you can make is from an honor sequence, particularly a 3 card sequence. You lead the top of the honor sequence. In suits, it is ok to lead from a 2 card honor sequence. Lead A from AKxx, K from KQxx, Q from QJxx, J from J10xx. In NT, however, you should only lead from a 3 card honor sequence or broken sequence. Lead  K from KQJ or KQ10, Q from QJ10 or QJ9, and J from J109 or J108. The reason it is ok to lead from a 2 card sequence in suits is, it is unlikely you have more than one or two tricks in a non-trump suit. But, in NT, you are hoping to establish tricks, so you hope partner has something to fill in for you if you only have a 2 card sequence.|
PG| ***** 191 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
HT|d|FP|1|cs|1|CP|4|at|^-
{        Transcript from the Lesson       }
^-|CP||FP||cp|8|AT|^C@2^Y@3
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, with an unprotected honor, if you choose to lead the suit, lead low (assuming you don't have a doubleton). From Jxx, if you choose to lead the suit (for example, partner bid it), lead low. Some people think you should lead an honor if you have it in partner's suit. But, that is not correct. Remember, you want your honor to capture one of the opponent's honors.|
PG| ***** 192 ***** |


AT|

On the other hand, you should lead low from three to an honor in partner's suit. Lead low from Kxx, Qxx or Jxx. Note that a few people lead K from AK, but that is not common practice any more.|
PG| ***** 193 ***** |


AT|

If leading a suit without an honor sequence, lead 4th best from an unprotected honor. Also lead low from 3 to an honor, as previously discussed, whether or not it is in partner's suit and lead high from a doubleton. You always lead "high-low" to show a doubleton. You you should avoid leading a doubleton, but if you think it is the right suit, lead high, even if you have an honor.|
PG| ***** 194 ***** |


AT|

Now, let's discuss what to lead from 3 small. Remember lead low from three to an honor. From three small, there is not general agreement. It comes down to the following tradeoff. Would you rather have partner know you don't have an honor, or that you don't have a doubleton. Most experts, who like to count hands out, prefer low from 3 small. However, most people on BBO prefer high from three small.|
PG| ***** 195 ***** |


AT|

As I said, if you lead low, then partner knows you do not have a doubleton because if you have a doubleton you lead high. However, if you also lead high from 3 small, then partner does not know whether you have two or three. But, as was said, on BBO, the preference is to lead high from three small. |
PG| ***** 196 ***** |


AT|

That may be okay because most people don't count out hands and it doesn't really help them to know you have three. But, it does help them to know you don't have an honor. So, on BBO leading high from three small is probably better (although I personally play low when playing with expert partners).|
PG| ***** 197 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%
HT|d|FP|1|cs|1|CP|4|at|^-
{        Transcript from the Lesson       }
^-|CP||FP||cp|8|AT|^C@2^Y@3
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Some people lead the middle card from three. That is called MUD for "Middle Up Down." I think that is not a very good approach partner often can't tell if the middle card is high or low so you get the worst of both worlds. Either agree to lead high, to deny an honor, or to lead low, to show count, but don't pick middle.|
PG| ***** 198 ***** |


AT|

Now if leading partner's suit, there is an exception. If you have supported partner;s suit, then it is okay to lead high from three small to show him you don't have an honor. But, if you have not supported partner's suit, then it is more important for partner to know how many you have then whether or not you have an honor. Partner has honors, and dummy may have some honors and partner can often work out where the honors are. But, it is nice for partner to know how many you started with, so he can figure out how many declarer has, and discard appropriately.|
PG| ***** 199 ***** |


AT|

Therefore, if you have not supported partner's suit and have 3 small, lead low. But, other than that, lead high (if you either have supported partner or are leading an unbid suit).

This concludes this week's session.|
PG| ***** 200 ***** |


